  </head>
  <body>
    <header class="site">
      <div class="wrap nav">
        <a class="brand" href="/">
          <img src="/CapyGoldIcon.png" alt="ParkerPixie gold capybara icon" />
          <span>ParkerPixie</span>
        </a>
        <nav class="nav-right" aria-label="Primary">
          <a class="nav-link" href="/about/">About</a>
          <a class="nav-link" href="/blog/">Blog</a>
          <a class="nav-btn" href="/contact/">Contact</a>
        </nav>
      </div>
    </header>

    <main class="shell">
      <header class="post">
        <div class="sparkles" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        <div class="kicker">ParkerPixie Blog</div>
        <h1>{title} ‚ú®</h1>
        <p class="sub">{subtitle}</p>
        <div class="meta">
          <span>{date}</span>
          <div class="tags">
            {tags.map((t) => <span class="tag">{t}</span>)}
          </div>
        </div>
        {cover && (
          <figure class="cover">
            <img src={cover} alt="The ADHD Friendship Loop illustration" loading="eager" />
          </figure>
        )}
      </header>

      <article class="content">
        <section class="insight" role="note" aria-label="Pixie Insight">
          <div class="badge">Pixie<br/>Insight</div>
          <p style="margin:0;">
            My silence has never been proof I don‚Äôt care‚Äîit‚Äôs just the part of the story where my brain pulls the fire alarm and hides in the bathroom.
          </p>
        </section>

        <p>
          I‚Äôve been thinking a lot about friendships lately‚Äîespecially the part where I‚Äôm
          <em>really</em> good at starting them and then somehow vanish like a mythical woodland creature
          the moment life throws me a mild inconvenience.
        </p>

        <p>
          So, hi. It‚Äôs me. The problem is (sometimes) me. But not for the reasons people assume.
        </p>

        <p>
          I know I go quiet. I know I disappear. I know I leave messages sitting there like sad little
          orphans in my notification center. And I also know it probably looks like I don‚Äôt care‚Ä¶
          when the truth is actually the exact opposite.
        </p>

        <p>
          If anything, I care so much it paralyzes me.
        </p>

        <p>
          After a lot of therapy, trauma recovery, and realizing I‚Äôm basically a walking Venn diagram of
          ‚ÄúADHD but make it emotional,‚Äù I finally have language for the friendship pattern that has ruled
          my life without my consent:
          <strong>the ADHD Friendship Loop.</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="pull">
          I don‚Äôt lose people because I stop caring. I lose people because my brain glitches, shame piles on,
          and I feel too awkward to hit ‚Äúsend.‚Äù
        </div>

        <h2>The ADHD Friendship Loop (play-by-play)</h2>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">1. The Connection Surge</h3>
        <p>
          This is my Olympic event. I meet someone and <strong>BOOM</strong>‚Äîfireworks, serotonin, the whole
          ‚ÄúOMG you‚Äôre my people‚Äù montage starts playing.
        </p>
        <p>
          I‚Äôm replying instantly. I‚Äôm sending memes. I‚Äôm making plans. I‚Äôm voice-noting like we‚Äôve known each
          other for ten years. My phone lights up and so do I.
        </p>
        <p>
          If dopamine were a drug, this would be the dealer.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">2. The Life-Load Pile-On</h3>
        <p>
          Then we hit the part of the movie where everything gets‚Ä¶ a lot.
        </p>
        <p>
          Work stress. Parenting chaos. Executive dysfunction. My nervous system deciding to schedule a mental
          breakdown on a random Tuesday. Add a pinch of childhood trauma. You know, the usual seasoning.
        </p>
        <p>
          And just like that, the social battery isn‚Äôt ‚Äúlow‚Äù‚Äîit‚Äôs <em>dead-dead</em>. Not ‚Äúneeds charging.‚Äù
          I mean <strong>gone</strong>. Zero percent. Needs a tow truck.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">3. The Shutdown Mode</h3>
        <p>
          This is where my brain gently (rudely) announces:
          <em>‚ÄúHey girl, no more humans. Crawl into your emotional cave immediately.‚Äù</em>
        </p>
        <p>
          It‚Äôs not that I <em>want</em> to hide from people. It‚Äôs that my nervous system is basically
          a chihuahua in a thunderstorm: trembling, wide-eyed, and convinced that one more notification
          might actually kill me.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">4. The Shame Spiral</h3>
        <p>
          Here‚Äôs the fun part. (Said with the heaviest sarcasm.)
        </p>
        <p>
          Now I feel guilty for disappearing. So instead of just‚Ä¶ answering the text like a normal mammal,
          I stare at it like it‚Äôs a final exam I forgot to study for.
        </p>
        <p>My thoughts go something like:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>‚ÄúThey think I‚Äôm a flaky jerk.‚Äù</li>
          <li>‚ÄúI ruined the friendship.‚Äù</li>
          <li>‚ÄúI didn‚Äôt reply for too long.‚Äù</li>
          <li>‚ÄúThis is why I can‚Äôt have nice things.‚Äù</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Meanwhile, the friend probably just thinks I‚Äôm busy making dinner.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">5. The Re-Entry Paralysis</h3>
        <p>
          <strong>THIS. IS. MY. VILLAIN. ORIGIN. STORY.</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          At this point, so much time has passed that replying feels like showing up to a party after everyone
          already went home and the host is in pajamas doing dishes.
        </p>
        <p>
          I don‚Äôt want to seem dramatic or weird. So I wait for the ‚Äúright moment‚Äù to respond:
          the mythical, perfectly calm afternoon where I can craft the perfect message that explains everything.
        </p>
        <p>
          Spoiler alert: that moment never arrives.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is where friendships quietly die‚Äînot because anything went
          wrong, but because my brain hit a glitch and I felt too awkward to reboot.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1.4rem;">6. The Lonely Loop</h3>
        <p>
          Now I miss people. I want connection. I scroll through old messages and feel the ache of ‚ÄúI really
          liked them‚Ä¶ I hope they‚Äôre okay.‚Äù
        </p>
        <p>
          But the shame trap is locked, and my brain needs the emotional equivalent of a SWAT team to break in.
        </p>
        <p>
          So what do I do? The most ADHD thing ever:
          <strong>I make new friends and repeat the exact same pattern.</strong>
        </p>

        <div class="pull">
          I am nothing if not consistent in my chaos. But consistency is not the same as doom‚Äîespecially
          once I can name the pattern.
        </div>

        <h2>What my silence is <em>not</em></h2>

        <p>If you‚Äôre one of my friends, here‚Äôs the part I need you to know the most:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>It is <strong>never</strong> because I don‚Äôt care.</li>
          <li>It is <strong>never</strong> because I‚Äôm mad at you.</li>
          <li>It is <strong>never</strong> because I‚Äôve ‚Äúmoved on.‚Äù</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          When I go quiet, it‚Äôs almost always one (or more) of these:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>A) ADHD brain did the ‚Äúlater‚Äù thing.</strong><br />
            I saw your message at a bad moment ‚Üí meant to come back ‚Üí forgot ‚Üí
            remembered at 2:07 a.m. ‚Üí panicked.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>B) Trauma brain hit the eject button.</strong><br />
            A tiny, innocent message somehow set off an old alarm, and my system went
            straight to <em>‚ÄúWe‚Äôve upset them. All is lost. FLEE.‚Äù</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>C) My personal life is on metaphorical fire.</strong><br />
            Parenting, work, home life, recovery, my own healing journey‚Äîsometimes it‚Äôs
            all burning at once and the only thing I can manage is ‚Äúkeep everyone alive and
            vaguely fed.‚Äù
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          None of this is personal. None of this is a reflection of how much I love you.
          None of this means I don‚Äôt want connection.
        </p>

        <h2>What I‚Äôm trying to practice now</h2>

        <p>
          I‚Äôm not writing this to make excuses. I‚Äôm writing it because I want to understand
          myself instead of hating myself‚Äîand because I want to do better.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Micro-responses.</strong>
            Letting ‚ÄúI saw this and I love you, more later üíú‚Äù be enough instead of waiting
            until I can write a dissertation.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Messy re-entry.</strong>
            Sending the text even when it‚Äôs been ‚Äútoo long,‚Äù and trusting that the people
            who are my people will be glad I showed up, period.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Reality checks.</strong>
            Reminding myself: ‚ÄúThey probably think you‚Äôre busy, not evil‚Äù instead of letting
            my inner troll run the commentary.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Trauma-aware boundaries.</strong>
            Not forcing myself into constant availability, but also not letting fear
            drive the car every time connection feels vulnerable.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <div class="pull">
          I want to show up‚Äîconsistently, honestly, and without drowning in guilt.
          I want to let people back in without feeling like I‚Äôm crawling out of the grave
          of every unanswered text.
        </div>

        <h2>If you relate‚Ä¶</h2>

        <p>
          If you see yourself in this loop, I hope you feel a little less alone. You‚Äôre not
          broken. Your brain is just running a very specific, very dramatic script it has
          rehearsed for years.
        </p>

        <p>
          You‚Äôre allowed to pause the script. You‚Äôre allowed to write a new scene where you
          send the ‚Äúhey, I disappeared, I‚Äôm sorry, I still care about you‚Äù message and let
          that be enough.
        </p>

        <h2>If you‚Äôre my friend‚Ä¶</h2>

        <p>
          Thank you for sticking around while I figure this out. Thank you for letting me
          be human and glitchy and late and ‚Äúoops I thought about replying a thousand times
          in my head‚Äù and still worthy of connection.
        </p>

        <p>
          I‚Äôm not perfect. I never will be. But I‚Äôm trying‚Äîintentionally, awkwardly, and
          with as much honesty as I can give.
        </p>

        <div class="hr"></div>

        <p class="mantra">
          <span class="dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>
          <span>
            <strong>Mantra:</strong>
            My silence is not my truth. I can always come back, even late.
          </span>
        </p>

        <footer class="foot">
          <div>‚Äî Parker</div>
          <nav class="share" aria-label="Share this post">
            <button class="btn" id="copyLinkBtn" type="button">Copy Link</button>
            <a class="btn" id="fbShare" href="#" rel="noopener">Share on Facebook</a>
            <button class="btn" id="nativeShareBtn" type="button" hidden>Share‚Ä¶</button>
            <a class="btn" href="/blog/">Back to Blog</a>
          </nav>
        </footer>
      </article>
    </main>

    <div id="toast" role="status" aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">Link copied ‚ú®</div>

    <script type="module">
      const url = new URL(window.location.href);
      const titleMeta = document.title || "ParkerPixie Blog";

      const copyBtn = document.getElementById("copyLinkBtn");
      const fbA = document.getElementById("fbShare");
      const nativeBtn = document.getElementById("nativeShareBtn");
      const toast = document.getElementById("toast");

      const fbShareUrl = new URL("https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php");
      fbShareUrl.searchParams.set("u", url.href);
      fbA.href = fbShareUrl.toString();

      copyBtn?.addEventListener("click", async () => {
        try {
          if (navigator.clipboard?.writeText) {
            await navigator.clipboard.writeText(url.href);
          } else {
            const ta = document.createElement("textarea");
            ta.value = url.href;
            document.body.appendChild(ta);
            ta.select();
            document.execCommand("copy");
            ta.remove();
          }
          showToast();
        } catch {
          window.prompt("Copy this URL:", url.href);
        }
      });

      if (navigator.share) {
        nativeBtn.hidden = false;
        nativeBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
          navigator.share({ title: titleMeta, url: url.href }).catch(() => {});
        });
      }

      let toastTimer;
      function showToast() {
        toast.classList.add("show");
        clearTimeout(toastTimer);
        toastTimer = setTimeout(() => toast.classList.remove("show"), 1400);
      }
    </script>
